      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tribute to a Lost Parent</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Judy Payne letter replies to Dec 20 letter that suggested toning down advertising keyed to family holidays out of consideration for children who lost parents on Sept 11</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Holidays of Pain'' (letter, Dec. 20):</p>
        <p>While I can understand the pain and sense of loss felt on holidays like Mother's Day and Father's Day by children who have lost parents, I see no reason to shield them from reality by watering down the observance for others.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Holidays of Pain'' (letter, Dec. 20):</p>
        <p>While I can understand the pain and sense of loss felt on holidays like Mother's Day and Father's Day by children who have lost parents, I see no reason to shield them from reality by watering down the observance for others.</p>
        <p>Perhaps rather than changing these holidays, we could encourage these children to create projects in memory of their parents, not to be brought to a graveyard, as the letter writer indicates, but as a personal and family tribute to that parent, displayed with love in the children's homes.</p>
        <p>JUDY PAYNE  Lakewood, Calif., Dec. 20, 2001</p>
      </block>
